James Middleton Cox. Another name to etch into the annals of history, or perhaps just another footnote in the grand, exhausting narrative of American ambition. He was a man who dabbled in nearly every facet of public life, from the gritty aroma of printer’s ink to the polished halls of governance, only to ultimately be remembered for losing the [presidency of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States) in a rather spectacular fashion. Born with the rather quaint name James Monroe Cox, he later adopted "Middleton," perhaps in an attempt to sound more... substantial. A futile effort, as most are.

